    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Never published before this edition.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig>σ</orig><gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/><orig>α</orig><gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/><orig>σο</orig><choice><unclear>ι</unclear><unclear>ν</unclear><unclear>π</unclear></choice><gap reason="lost" atLeast="1" atMost="2" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><orig>ο</orig> <w lemma="ὅδε"><unclear>τ</unclear>όδε</w> <space atLeast="7" atMost="9" unit="character"/>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Intraduisibile.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Intraducibile.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>Only the final word is identifiable, meaning 'this object'. Therefore this inscription was probably a dedication. The omicron which precedes is necessarily the ending of a genitive, strengthening the impression that 
                 the lettering antidates the adoption of the standard alphabet at the end of the fifth century BC.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
